INSERT INTO notes VALUES(X'c516341b72704b4eabb2e785245f8389','Practical Guide to TOTP-Based 2FA in Rust Web Applications',replace('1. what is totp \n2. why use it \n3. how does it work \n4. implementing this in Rust. \n\n&nbsp;','\n',char(10)),'[]','2026-03-12T14:29:08.626657+00:00','2026-03-12T14:29:08.626657+00:00',X'ed42af204199419299e0965e2263d49e');
INSERT INTO notes VALUES(X'cb717e49760a4f91ba3f8e6e84eea79f','How to implement recovery codes',replace('Recovery codes are **one-time backup codes** that allow a user to log in if they lose access to their TOTP authenticator (phone, app, etc.). They are typically generated when enabling **2FA** and each code can be used **only once**.\n\nSince you already implemented **TOTP + email 2FA** in your system, recovery codes are a natural next security layer.\n\nBelow is a **production-grade approach** commonly used by systems like GitHub, Google, and GitLab.\n\n---\n\n# 1. Database Schema\n\nStore **hashed recovery codes**, never plaintext.\n\nExample table:\n\n```sql\ntwo_factor_recovery_codes\n```\n\nFields:\n\n```text\nid (uuid / ulid)\nuser_id\ncode_hash\nused (bool)\nused_at (timestamp nullable)\ncreated_at\n\n```\n\nExample SeaORM entity structure:\n\n```rust\npub struct Model {\n    pub id: Ulid,\n    pub user_id: Ulid,\n    pub code_hash: String,\n    pub used: bool,\n    pub used_at: Option<DateTime>,\n    pub created_at: DateTime,\n}\n\n```\n\nImportant:\n\n- store **hash(code),** not raw code,\n- allows safe storage if DB leaks\n\n---\n\n# 2. Generate Recovery Codes\n\nGenerate **8–10 random codes** when enabling TOTP.\n\nExample format:\n\n```\nA7F4-K9P2\nX2J8-Q4L1\nP9D3-T6R8\n\n```\n\nRust example:\n\n```rust\nuse rand::{distributions::Alphanumeric, Rng};\n\nfn generate_code() -> String {\n    let code: String = rand::thread_rng()\n        .sample_iter(&Alphanumeric)\n        .take(8)\n        .map(char::from)\n        .collect();\n\n    format!("{}-{}", &code[0..4], &code[4..8])\n}\n\n```\n\nGenerate multiple:\n\n```rust\nlet codes: Vec<String> = (0..10).map(|_| generate_code()).collect();\n\n```\n\n---\n\n# 3. Hash Before Saving\n\nUse a password-style hash (Argon2 or bcrypt).\n\nExample:\n\n```rust\nuse argon2::{Argon2, PasswordHasher};\nuse password_hash::SaltString;\n\nfn hash_code(code: &str) -> String {\n    let salt = SaltString::generate(&mut rand::thread_rng());\n    Argon2::default()\n        .hash_password(code.as_bytes(), &salt)\n        .unwrap()\n        .to_string()\n}\n\n```\n\nStore only the hash.\n\n---\n\n# 4. Display Codes Once\n\nReturn the **plaintext codes only once** to the user.\n\nExample response:\n\n```json\n{\n  "recoveryCodes": [\n    "A7F4-K9P2",\n    "X2J8-Q4L1",\n    "P9D3-T6R8"\n  ]\n}\n\n```\n\nTell user to:\n\n- download\n- print\n- store securely\n\nNever show them again.\n\n---\n\n# 5. Login Flow\n\nTypical 2FA verification step:\n\n```\nEnter TOTP code\nOR\nEnter recovery code\n\n```\n\nFlow:\n\n```\nif verify_totp() {\n    success\n}\nelse if verify_recovery_code() {\n    mark_code_used()\n    success\n}\nelse {\n    deny\n}\n\n```\n\n---\n\n# 6. Verify Recovery Code\n\nExample logic:\n\n```rust\nfn verify_recovery_code(input: &str, stored_hash: &str) -> bool {\n    Argon2::default()\n        .verify_password(input.as_bytes(), &PasswordHash::new(stored_hash).unwrap())\n        .is_ok()\n}\n\n```\n\nIf valid:\n\n```rust\ncode.used = true;\ncode.used_at = now();\n\n```\n\n---\n\n# 7. Regenerate Codes\n\nAllow user to regenerate codes.\n\nWhen regenerating:\n\n```\ndelete all old codes\ngenerate new ones\n\n```\n\nSecurity pattern used by Google and GitHub.\n\n---\n\n# 8. Security Best Practices\n\n### Limit attempts\n\nPrevent brute force:\n\n```\nmax attempts: 5\nlock for 10 minutes\n\n```\n\n---\n\n### Code length\n\nRecommended:\n\n```\n8–12 characters\n\n```\n\n---\n\n### Number of codes\n\nIndustry standard:\n\n```\n8 or 10 codes\n\n```\n\n---\n\n### Format for usability\n\nExample:\n\n```\nABCD-EFGH\n\n```\n\nUsers type it easily.\n\n---\n\n# 9. UI UX Pattern\n\nWhen enabling 2FA:\n\n```\nStep 1: Scan QR\nStep 2: Verify TOTP\nStep 3: Download Recovery Codes\n\n```\n\nExample UI text:\n\n```\nSave these recovery codes somewhere safe.\n\nEach code can be used once if you lose access to your authenticator app.\n\n```\n\n---\n\n# 10. Recommended API Endpoints\n\n```\nPOST /2fa/totp/enable\nPOST /2fa/totp/verify\nGET  /2fa/recovery-codes\nPOST /2fa/recovery-codes/regenerate\nPOST /2fa/recovery-codes/use\n\n```\n\n---\n\n# 11. Bonus: Offline-first systems\n\nSince you''re building **offline-first systems with SQLite + sync queue**, recovery codes can still work offline because:\n\n- Verification is **local**\n- Just check hash in SQLite\n- mark used\n- sync state later\n\n---\n\n:check_mark_button: **Best architecture summary**\n\n```\nTOTP enabled\n        │\n        ▼\nGenerate 10 recovery codes\n        │\n        ▼\nHash codes in DB\n        │\n        ▼\nShow plaintext once\n        │\n        ▼\nLogin accepts:\n   TOTP OR Recovery Code\n        │\n        ▼\nRecovery code marked used\n\n```\n\n---\n\n&nbsp;','\n',char(10)),'[]','2026-03-16T00:18:09.859878+00:00','2026-03-23T07:49:29.175657+00:00',X'e4a9def41a4247609e8eb54c76d82a3d');
INSERT INTO notes VALUES(X'94a6332e25ff47ccb1d838d564895537','Endpoints that require plugins',replace('1. change bank details\n  [PUT https://api.tranq.services/bank/details](https://api.tranq.services/bank/details)\n  1. found in Apollo\n2. Password change \n  1. POST\n    [https://api.tranq.services/user/profile/update-password](https://api.tranq.services/user/profile/update-password)\n  2. Found in Hera\n3. email update \n  1. POST\n    [https://api.tranq.services/user/profile/change-email](https://api.tranq.services/user/profile/change-email)\n  2. Found in Hera\n4. account deletion \n\n&nbsp;','\n',char(10)),'[]','2026-03-23T12:50:37.427146+00:00','2026-03-23T12:50:37.427146+00:00',X'e4a9def41a4247609e8eb54c76d82a3d');
INSERT INTO notes VALUES(X'd945c60f025a4a4d8ae16d0ed9e00a04','Resetting a commit',replace('Happens to everyone — don’t panic. The right fix depends on whether you’ve **already pushed to remote** or not.\n\n---\n\n## :mag: First question\n\nDid you run `git push` already?\n\n---\n\n# :check_mark_button: Case 1 — NOT pushed yet (easy)\n\nJust reset your branch:\n\n```bash\ngit reset --soft HEAD~1\n\n```\n\n- keeps your changes\n- removes the commit from history\n\nIf you want to discard changes too:\n\n```bash\ngit reset --hard HEAD~1\n\n```\n\n---\n\n# :check_mark_button: Case 2 — Already pushed to `main` (important)\n\n### :lock: Safe option (recommended for teams)\n\nUse **revert** (no history rewrite):\n\n```bash\ngit revert HEAD\ngit push\n\n```\n\n✔ creates a new commit that undoes the bad one  \n:check_mark: safe for shared branches  \n:check_mark: no breaking teammates\n\n---\n\n### :warning: Risky option (only if you''re alone on branch)\n\nRewrite history:\n\n```bash\ngit reset --hard HEAD~1\ngit push --force\n\n```\n\n🚨 This can break other people’s work if they’ve pulled `main`\n\n---\n\n## :brain: Quick rule of thumb\n\n- Team/shared branch → `**git revert**`\n- Solo / no one pulled → **force push is fine**\n\n---\n\n## :bulb: Bonus (clean workflow going forward)\n\nInstead of committing directly to `main`:\n\n```bash\ngit checkout -b fix/recovery-codes\n\n```\n\nThen push + PR.\n\n---\n\n&nbsp;','\n',char(10)),'[]','2026-03-23T15:59:30.556129+00:00','2026-03-23T15:59:30.556130+00:00',X'e4a9def41a4247609e8eb54c76d82a3d');
INSERT INTO notes VALUES(X'1377fcac160846bf8be8a95eec0fd5aa','Dreamscape 2026',replace('1. Learn Rust from basics to advanced concepts\n2. Build one zero dependency application — use the Rust standard library, the app should be non-trivial\n3. Implement an HTTP server, again zero deps.\n4. Maybe implement Redis.\n5. Build portfolio\n\n&nbsp;\n\n### Libraries to learn\n\n- tokio\n- future \n- std::sync\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe plan \n\n- learn Golang so well, begin freelancing the plunge into Rust\n\n&nbsp;\n\nCurrent freelance reality (Upwork-style, 2026):\n\n- **Node.js** — Median ~$25/hr, range $18–38/hr for backend gigs—highest volume by far. Quick CRUD, APIs, NestJS/Express stuff flies. Clients want it yesterday.\n- **Go** — Median ~$30/hr, up to $42–90/hr for seniors. Strong for scalable microservices, cloud-native. Good velocity, solid demand.\n- **Rust** — Premium when it hits (some gigs $45–80+/hr, especially Web3/blockchain, performance-critical, or low-level tools), but way fewer postings. Most "Rust" freelancers are niche: Solana stuff, WASM, high-perf backends, or rewriting legacy for latency wins. Not the daily bread for volume freelancing.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nYou''re mid-senior, so you could realistically start bidding at **$35–55/hr** on Go/Node gigs right now (position yourself as senior backend, mention your microservices). Even landing 10–15 billable hours/week at $40/hr = ~$1,600–2,400/month extra. At current ~1,380 NGN/USD, that''s another **2.2M–3.3M NGN/month** on top of your 400k job. That''s life-changing in Nigeria without quitting.\n\nRust "deepening" for low-level? Cool for long-term (Web3 infra, embedded, safety-critical), and it can command a premium. But the volume is lower, and clients rarely scream "I need a low-level Rust app!" — they scream "I need this backend fixed by Friday."  \n\nBurnout warning: 400k NGN job + serious side hustling + deep Rust study = Naija developer special (generator + Starlink roulette). Protect your sleep.\n\n**Verdict now: 8/10 plan, but execution order still mid.** With your experience, you could be pulling serious USD in 3–6 months on Go/Node while Rust becomes your flex/superpower. Don''t gate the bag behind more Rust mastery — the market doesn''t wait.\n\nWhat''s your current hourly rate target on freelance platforms? Any specific low-level Rust use cases you''re eyeing (Web3, embedded, infra tools)? Or portfolio links? That''d let me give sharper next steps instead of generic roast.\n\nGo collect, senior. Your 400k job is about to become pocket change. :rocket:””””"\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n### Resources \n\n- Master Rust + Axum [https://gruberb.github.io/bulletproof-rust-web/introduction.html](https://gruberb.github.io/bulletproof-rust-web/introduction.html)\n\n&nbsp;','\n',char(10)),'[]','2026-03-24T09:50:01.945904+00:00','2026-04-16T21:15:03.343850+00:00',X'ed42af204199419299e0965e2263d49e');
