INSERT INTO notes VALUES(X'b69ef6778a104407991f409ee9df3a92','Data sync',replace('## Two-Way Sync Approach\n\n### Architecture: Offline-first with sync queue + conflict resolution\n\n---\n\n### 1. Local write → queue → push to orchard\n\nEvery mutation (create/update/delete) in a Pinia store should:\n\n1. Write to local SQLite (as it does today via Tauri invoke)\n2. Push an entry to the local `sync_queue` — already exists with `table_name`, `record_identifier`, `operation` (CREATE/UPDATE/DELETE)\n3. When `useOnline()` becomes `true`, flush the queue by calling orchard''s REST/GraphQL endpoints in order, then pop each entry on success\n\n---\n\n### 2. Pull from orchard → merge into local\n\nOn app start (and on reconnect), fetch server-side changes since `last_synced_at`:\n\n- Each entity table needs a `server_updated_at` timestamp\n- Client sends its `last_synced_at` per workspace; orchard returns only records modified after that\n- Merge them into local SQLite, then update `last_synced_at`\n\n---\n\n### 3. Conflict resolution strategy\n\nSince both sides can change the same record while offline, you need a rule. The simplest that fits a personal notes/todo app:\n\n**Last-write-wins by `updated_at**` — compare local `updatedAt` vs server `updatedAt` and keep the newer one. No user-facing conflict dialogs needed.\n\nIf you want finer granularity later (e.g. notes with paragraph-level merging), you can layer in CRDT-style field merging, but LWW is sufficient for v1.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Sync trigger points\n\nEventAction`useOnline()` → trueFlush local queue → pull server changesApp foreground (Tauri focus event)Pull server changes if `last_synced_at` > N minutes agoAfter any mutationPush to queue; if online, flush immediately\n\n---\n\n### 5. Orchard side changes needed\n\n- Add sync endpoints per entity (or one generic `/sync` endpoint): accepts a `since` timestamp, returns changed records\n- Accept batch upsert/delete from client queue\n- The `sync_queue` entity already exists on orchard''s side — you can use it to track what the server still needs to push back (server → client direction)\n\n---\n\n### 6. The `syncing` indicator\n\nThe `syncing` ref already exists in the titlebar — wire it to a `useSyncStatus()` composable that tracks whether a flush is in progress, so the cloud icon animates during sync.\n\n---\n\n### Key constraint\n\nAll mutations must remain optimistic — the UI never waits for the server. The queue ensures eventual consistency. If a push fails, the entry stays in the queue and retries on the next flush.','\n',char(10)),'[]','2026-03-30T22:07:10.025266+00:00','2026-03-30T22:07:10.025267+00:00',X'8acc2c420fda43ae8636c9f39067e51d');
